					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>High Crimes To Close, Naropa Receives $1 Million, and Colorado Authors Tour</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 3-05-08</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/highcrimes.gif" align="right" width="350" height="263" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

											<tr>
							<td>&nbsp;</td>
							<td class="image-caption" align="right">Caption: High Crimes Mystery Bookshop, photo courtesy of HighCrimesBooks.com.</td>
						</tr>
					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>Alicia Wallace recently reported in the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.dailycamera.com/news/2008/feb/20/moving-to-the-net-a-new-chapter-for-high-crimes/" title="Daily Camera">Daily Camera</a> that Boulder&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.highcrimesbooks.com/" title="High Crimes Mystery Bookshop">High Crimes Mystery Bookshop</a> will shut its doors on Pearl Street on March 15, and owner Cynthia Nye will convert the operation to an online, mail-order-only business.&nbsp; Although many of the mysteries High Crimes stocks feature surprising twists, in the case of this store closing, the usual suspects are to blame.&nbsp; Nye cites decreased foot traffic and fewer book purchases, as well as these problems: 
<br />
<blockquote><p>
&#8220;Book publishers tapering back author tours; the inverse relationship of rent prices to profits; the convenience of mass-market retailers like Barnes &amp; Noble and Amazon.com; and customers&#8217; negative perception of parking in downtown Boulder.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>
On a more positive note for the Boulder literary community, a mystery donor has given a posthumous gift of $1 million to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.naropa.edu/" title="Naropa University">Naropa University</a>, as reported by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/28/mystery-donor-leaves-1-million-to-naropa/" title="Jean Torkelson in the Rocky Mountain News">Jean Torkelson in the Rocky Mountain News</a>.&nbsp; Allen Ginsberg, who founded the university&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.naropa.edu/academics/graduate/writingpoetics/index.cfm" title="Jack Kerouac School of Disembodied Poetics">Jack Kerouac School of Disembodied Poetics</a>, must be smiling somewhere.
</p>
<p>
Finally, I enjoyed meeting many local authors at the networking event NewWest sponsored in Boulder last week.&nbsp; I encouraged them to send me information about their upcoming tours and events, and several of them responded:
</p>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.authoralangottlieb.com/" title="Alan Gottlieb">Alan Gottlieb</a>, a Denver author and former <I>Denver Post</I> reporter who recently released his novel <I>Ultimate Excursions</I>, has <a target="_blank" href="http://www.authoralangottlieb.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=16&amp;Itemid=29" title="several readings scheduled in Colorado">several readings scheduled in Colorado</a>, including an appearance at Borders in Aurora on March 8 (2 p.m.) and at the <a target="_blank" href="http://boulderbookstore.booksense.com/NASApp/store/IndexJsp;jsessionid=abciQBBcrc4OI815Z-WHr?s=storeevents&amp;eventId=369726" title="Boulder Book Store">Boulder Book Store</a> on March 26 (7:30 p.m.).
</p>
<p>
Boulder author and vampire enthusiast <a target="_blank" href="http://www.lyndahilburnauthor.com/" title="Lynda Hillbrun">Lynda Hillbrun</a>, whose <a target="_blank" href="http://www.myspace.com/lyndahilburn" title="MySpace site features plenty of cleavage and fangs">MySpace site features plenty of cleavage and fangs</a>, will be signing her new novel, <I>The Vampire Shrink</I>, at the Barnes &amp; Noble in Thornton on March 8 (2 p.m.).&nbsp; She will also be on hand for this year&#8217;s Horrorfest in Denver (April 18-20).&nbsp; Do vampires need to drink more blood at high altitudes than they do at sea level?&nbsp;  I&#8217;m just wondering.
</p>
<p>
And check out the Yellow Pine Reading Series tonight, March 5, at Boulder&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.wildsagecohousing.org/" title="Wild Sage Community House ">Wild Sage Community House </a>(1650 Zamia, 7:15 p.m.).&nbsp; Five local authors, including poets <a target="_blank" href="http://sherylluna.blogspot.com/" title="Sheryl Luna ">Sheryl Luna </a>and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.think360arts.org/ya/residency/dana_elkun.htm" title="Dana Elkun">Dana Elkun</a>, will read their work.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
